USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It's funny how Barack Obama, the smartest president in the world, with schoolboy zeal, repeats the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself considered the dumbest, on the Afghan issue.
When he finally revealed his long-awaited Afghan doctrine, it turned out that he had copied it from Bush's Iraq script three years earlier.
Not only does he use the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, but he didn't hesitate to use the name of Bush's January 2007 statement as the title of his own declaration: "A new way forward".
Three years ago, he himself criticized Bush's idea of sending fresh military reinforcements to civil war-torn Iraq as "an irresponsible and consequently disastrous decision".
But the ensuing months showed that Bush's strategy, based on the recommendations of his field commanders, was the only one possible, and so successful that today Iraq is not even mentioned in the news.
It didn't improve Bush's reputation, but it did leave his successor with a much more grateful starting position than one might expect.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will happen again.
He was again asked to increase the military contingent by field commanders, most notably the top commander of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who, despite his subordinate's custom, sharply criticized the hesitant shooters in the White House.
He asked for 40,000 men to turn the tide.
The president hesitated for three months, but he couldn't think of anything better, so he at least cheated the general out of 10,000 soldiers.
He was able to extort the promise of another 5,000 from Europe, even though he had originally counted on at least 10.
The most problematic part of Obama's strategy seems to be his intention to begin withdrawing troops from Afghanistan as soon as 18 months from now and finish the process within three years.
Many doubt that a half-pay rise will yield the same fruit as the Iraq action.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well-ordered, its leaders honoring the agreement.
The Afghan situation is the opposite - no one can be trusted and no agreements are being kept.
Badly prepared in these conditions are the Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing masters every day as they see fit.
Political institutions, even if they are formally established, will remain a suburban village, under which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to flourish.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extremely difficult because of the opaque relationship that further complicates the Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Nor does building an "accessible state", which is the minimalist goal of the entire operation, seem very realistic.
The timeline of Obama's strategy is striking with its voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only gotten worse and is now on the verge of exploding.
To believe that soldiers sent into the war to "return home" will be able to perform a miracle here, is something only a truly romantic, untouched soul can believe.
From a political point of view, it is irresponsible to set a date for the withdrawal of troops, as the Taliban will see it as an implicit admission of American defeat.
The recent NATO summit has shown that the willingness of Europeans to participate in combat operations in Afghanistan is declining.
European politicians cannot and do not want to explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy is connected to the war in the foothills of the Indus.
Another factor that could radically affect the situation is the developments around Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions on Iran fail to work, the United States will face the overwhelming question of whether to try to resolve the problem by military force.
The answer to that will be at the time when Obama says America will move to a victorious withdrawal from Afghanistan.
But any such solution would also mean a dramatic turn in the Afghan situation.
The only thing that's patched up for Barack Obama is the fact that we're three years away from the presidential election, so there's plenty of time for him to come up with another strategy if this one turns out to be a total failure.
