Czech discovery: a substance that also works on 'live' HIV viruses
A team of Czech and German scientists are testing new compounds that can slow the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works against viruses that have already acquired immunity to the drugs.
In some cases, this outweighs the fact that the compound does not have the same potency as some of the medicines already available against the common variant.
AIDS is still incurable.
However, a mixture of drugs that prevent HIV from multiplying in the body can significantly prolong the life of patients.
However, their use is associated with a number of side effects.
In addition, incomplete suppression of viral replication results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which drugs are no longer effective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Czech Academy of Sciences, VŠCHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to tackle virus resistance.
They showed that substances called metalcarboranes interact with the protein responsible for HIV replication.
Metal carbons are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a way that no other drug in use today can, and therefore they can overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work, the scientists come up with new 'enhanced' compounds prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the viral protein.
Metal-carbonates have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages of boron, hydrogen, and carbon atoms are joined by a metal atom, in this case, cobalt.
A Treacherous and Resistant Virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV protease-induced cleavage of HIV, no mature infectious viral particles would be produced.
When we stop HIV protease, we also stop the virus spreading in the patient's body, the scientists explain in a press release issued by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Czech Academy of Sciences.
In a paper published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of keys (see table) are connected by a short organic chain that is then systematically modified.
Slightly weaker, but more reliable
The effects of this HIV protease inhibitor series have been tested in test tubes and against resistant variants derived from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of metal carbonates on the common variant of the enzyme is not as strong as that of clinically used drugs, but it is not lost on resistant variants against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action and their other properties such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical modifications make metalcarboranes interesting compounds for further research aimed at designing effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlina Rezeczová, head of the Structural Biology Laboratory of the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
