Today's 20 and 30-year-olds view their parents as the first days of the Chilean experiment in capitalism, and they don't want that kind of livelihood for themselves, he says.
It is the child that makes the enormous demands on the parents' time, he says.
A mother must sacrifice at least two years of her social life.
Then there are the controversial issues of props -- "You have to rebuild your apartment" -- and the strategy -- "You have to have a resume ready by the time your child is nine months old for good preschool education.
Most of his friends want to settle for one child, says Che, but not two.
We are the first generation with higher nutritional standards, he says.
We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
The UN group has drawn up a plan to reduce emissions.
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- characterized by far-reaching unprecedented attitudes and mutual blame -- focused again on Friday on the release of a document that proposes ambitious reductions in greenhouse gas emissions over the next 40 years with industrialized nations bearing the brunt of the burden in the near term.
The text, which could provide a basis for a final political agreement on the regulation of greenhouse gases, highlights the remaining obstacles as well as illuminating the way forward.
But there was important progress in the negotiations, which have come at a bad time with over 100 world leaders arriving in Copenhagen next week.
Created by an ad hoc UN working group, this text subtly states how much money rich countries should give to poor countries to deal with global warming in the short and long term.
And it provides a whole range of choices for key issues, including how to develop and manage emerging economies so that they can limit their carbon output and what the upper limit of global temperature rise should be that policymakers are still able to tolerate.
This gives the process a great deal of flexibility, says John Coequyt, chief executive of the Sierra Club of Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, cut from 180 pages of the text of the talks to focus on what the top UN climate official, Yvo de Boer, described as "the big picture".
It outlines a possible agreement whereby industrialised nations could collectively reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by the year from 1990 levels, while major developing countries could reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent during this period.
Together, the countries would reduce emissions by between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union on Friday made a hasty pledge to provide $3.6 trillion over the next three years to help poorer countries embrace climate change adaptation -- from managing floods and droughts to preventing deforestation.
But still, Friday featured the same kind of verbal fireworks that dominated the interviews last week.
US special envoy for climate change, Todd Stern, rejected a speech demanding binding greenhouse gas emission cuts for industrialized countries, compared to voluntary ones for major emerging economies, if they were not funded by the developed world.
The move signaled that the Obama administration had taken a tougher line against China than Bush administration officials had just two years ago.
The United States will not sign the treaty without major developing countries' transfer and implementation of the actions, Stern said, who also complained that the text is not sufficient to secure the restrictions and should be vetted by external observers.
Stern's comments came an hour after Chinese Vice Foreign Minister He Yafei told the US chief climate negotiator that either a lack of "communal wisdom" or "extreme irresponsibility" had led to the announcement earlier in the week that the United States would not help China financially to deal with global warming.
With the future of the economic trajectory of the world's major powers at stake, friction has broken out both within the developing world and between the industrialized world and emerging economies.
The current fight is more about preserving individual economies than the planet, between China and the United States over their respective commitments, while poorer nations point out that two dozen of the world's most influential countries are ignoring the scientific imperative to take stronger action.
Ricardo Ulate, delegate from Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that major powers were fighting over who should bear the cost of limiting greenhouse gases, while vulnerable countries had become much more aggressive in finding ways to prevent large emitters from acting responsibly.
It's clearly a game about the new economic hegemony that's emerging, said Ulate, who also serves as regional advisor on regional climate change in Mexico and Central America for the International Conservation Union.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to climate change have indicated they would like to continue to push for a legally binding agreement in Copenhagen, but most of the main participants said the best outcome of the talks would be a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which has 43 members, drafted a 24-page draft agreement last Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who led an international climate negotiation for the European Commission, said that the push by small island nations "has created a political impetus for the entire political process" in part because they are now united and demanding action from rising economies like China and India.
The negotiations took on a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that they had to resolve most of the remaining issues before the heads of government could reach an agreement.
High-ranking officials, such as India's environment minister, Jairam Ramesh, and China's deputy minister, have disembarked from planes and flown through the halls of the Bella Center for a closed-door meeting and new conferences to lay out their demands, which will be considered next week.
The sheer scale of the gathering -- 13,000 people moving in and out of the convention center every day, guitar-playing activists staging nightly shows ironizing the countries they thought they were sending them, and hand-to-hand transmission of proposals on paper rather than email -- was driven by challenge.
The intensity is only an extension: almost all the key ministers were present in Copenhagen, and earlier in the day 60 heads of state.
We've made it to the top of the charts, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, the assistant secretary for global policy at the International Conservation Fund.
Heavy weights coming in.
Britain's first train at 140 miles an hour redefined this Monday's feeling
At 5:13 a.m. on Monday morning, a whistle cut through the darkness to signal the departure of a train that would bring about a transport revolution in Britain.
The first high-speed passenger train in the country will reach a speed of 140 miles per hour and will run from Ashford in Kent to St Pancras in London, covering the distance of 58 miles in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, the transport minister, then joined Mrs Kelly Holmes and boarded the first high-speed passenger train out of London.
He hopes the new service will eventually connect Britain to an international network of fast, reliable trains and link the large agglomerations of the Midlands, the North and Scotland to London.
The proposed proposed new roadmap for the European Union's transport policy is based on the principle of 'a single market for all' and is designed to ensure that the transport sector is not left behind.
In theory, the three main political parties have been won over to this vision.
But the tens of billions of pounds needed to build the new national rail network, the inevitable competition for projects, and concerns about environmental degradation have now slowed Britain's high-speed railway construction.
High Speed Two (HS2), a company formed in January to provide the government with a feasibility study, submitted its report to Lord Adonis on December 30, as reported by the Times.
She provided him with a detailed route map of the next planned high-speed railway.
The new London-West Midland route was designed to operate within five metres in urban areas and districts where the impact on the environment could be problematic.
In the open country, the final route was planned to be 25 m.
HS2 also envisages the designation of three options for the extensive high-speed network leading north.
Lord Adonis will answer in the spring.
The preferred choice is a Y-shaped configuration where one high-speed line should lead to the West Midlands.
The line would be divided near Birmingham with one branch running from the Pennines to Manchester and Scotland and the other running north-east to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
One of the tracks should lead to Scotland.
"It seems to have been the most efficient choice", said a railway expert.
Once it's finished, the travel time between London and Edinburgh will be cut to two hours and 40 minutes.
The first stage, which will not open until 2025, could enable passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes compared with more than one hour at present.
The proposals would allow trains to run at 2250 miles an hour, making the British network the fastest in Europe.
The initial track is already designed to carry trains 400 m long, capable of carrying 1100 people.
Up to 18 sets could be operated every hour on the London to Birmingham route.
This means that the London terminal would be able to handle up to 20,000 passengers an hour if needed.
Due to capital constraints, it is assumed that the existing station would be extended to accommodate the high-speed network.
Railway industry experts say that only San Pancras International or Euston offers such potential.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not he intends to implement this scheme, but extensive public consultation and planning procedures mean that no final decision will be reached before the general election.
Even if he can get the wheels moving, the grid should be built in pieces.
Trains should first be put into service not on high-speed lines but on existing lines north of Birmingham and keep journey times between London and Scotland above three hours.
This is considered the crucial junction point for securing the transition from airplanes to trains, the landmark for the railway revolution.
The taxpayers paid off a £75,000 mortgage on the Tory orangery.
Alan Duncan, the Tory frontbench MP in the House of Commons, was paid thousands of pounds by the taxpayers last year for the orangery he built in his constituency house.
The prison party spokesman, who was demoted by David Cameron for complaining that MPs were living "on rations", raised his mortgage to £75,000 to build an oak-clad extension to his second house in Rutland.
He was allowed to charge special interest, hundreds of pounds a month in total to the taxpayers.
The General Authorities approved the demands in time and so were not heard by Sir Thomasen Legge, who was conducting the audit of the Members' expenditure.
Mr. Duncan, one of the richest members of Parliament, owns two two-story country houses in his constituency of Rutland and Melton.
The houses are worth approximately a million pounds.
There's a kitchen, a living room and a dining room on the ground floor, but the finance department agreed with me that Mr. Duncan needs more space.
Last year, he added a winter garden to the house, which is designated in the plans as an "orange grove".
Neighbors describe it as "a fun and treat greenhouse".
Mr. Duncan was not asked to provide any explanation for the increased loan during the last review by the Committee on General Standards and Privileges in the last mortgage settlement.
The committee told him last month that he broke the rules after reviewing his expenses.
In 2004, Mr Duncan exchanged a mortgage security of £27,1406 from his London estate for a house in his constituency which he had bought in 1991, the year before he became a Member of Parliament.
Documents released this week showed that Mr. Duncan was claiming approximately 1,400 pounds a month in mortgage interest until March of last year.
In April his claims increased to over £1,800 a month.
The interest RBS was paying on Mr Duncan's mortgage could not have changed at this time, indicating that it was all earmarked to finance a loan of £75,000.
The standard variable RBS mortgage rate fell from 7.94% in December 2007 to 4% in March this year, where it has remained.
The latest municipal records show that Mr Duncan continued to claim £1,250 a month in May this year.
Mr. Duncan left his job as shadow House leader in September after an undercover informant videotaped him saying that members had to survive on "a rations" after the spending scandal.
"Basically, it's nationalized, you have to live on a ration and you're treated like a s**t".
He said: "I have spent my money for my garden and my right and a little of what was needed.
And I could claim the whole damn share, but I'm not gonna do it".
The MP, a millionaire from a former career as an oil trader, was first asked to explain his May issue when it emerged he had claimed thousands of pounds for his garden, before the Financial Conduct Authority approved it as "may be considered excessive".
One of the activists dug a pound-shaped hole in Mr Duncan's lawn in protest after it was revealed that he had been claiming £4,000 for three years.
When asked last night about the mortgage increase, Mr. Duncan said, "It was for a capital increase, which was approved by both the Treasury and subsequently the Legislature".
He added, "this is not a matter of hiding and clicking or breaking rules or anything.
It's absolutely straight down, by the book, legitimate and that's it.
There are many ways to do it that are cleaner and simpler".
Come all of you and take a close look at the Brighton Coast hut with the advent calendar.
