A strong mobilization in Copenhagen and around the world against climate change.
Tens of thousands of people took to the streets on Saturday to demand a strong and binding agreement to combat global warming, to be adopted at the Copenhagen conference, demonstrating around the world and in Copenhagen, where police arrested hundreds of people on that occasion.
At least 30,000 people, according to police sources and 100,000, according to organizers, marched in the Danish capital in cold weather to mark the UN climate conference, which aims to adopt a deal by Friday that could enter into force on January 1, 2013.
Connie Hedegaard, the Danish president of the climate conference, said that the growing global mobilization, as evidenced by the current demonstrations, has contributed to the "political toll" of a failure in Copenhagen being too high.
According to AFP, the incidents in the Danish capital occurred shortly after the march began, when a group of about 300 protesters dressed in black began breaking down the exhibits with paving stones and hammers.
The riot police responded immediately.
In total, police announced the arrest of 600 to 700 people, specifying that they were mainly members of the "Blacks Blocks", ultra-radical separatist groups that had already manifested themselves in April at the NATO summit in Strasbourg, eastern France.
The Coalition Climate Justice Action (CJA), one of the organizers of the event, condemned the conditions under which hundreds of radicals were arrested "without distinction", and stressed that about a hundred of them were in handcuffs and in chains "kept in the streets on Saturday night" despite the extreme winter.
After leaving Parliament, the procession calmly made their way to the Bella Center, where the proceedings were taking place.
The protesters stopped about 500 meters from the building without trying to get inside.
A podium was set up for the speakers, before which a candlelight spiritual meeting was held with former South African Archbishop Desmond Tutu of Cape Town.
Most of the protesters came by bus and train from major European cities, and in addition to Africans, there were also a large number of Asian participants, including a few Chinese and Koreans.
Nearly 3,000 people, mostly dressed in blue coats, formed the first gathering in Copenhagen in the early hours of the morning, at the urging of Friends of the Earth, who wanted to create "blue waves" for a "fair climate".
Today we are taking to the streets to demand the payment of the ecological debt in favor of the South, explained Lidy Nacpil, a Filipino activist from the Jubilee South Coalition in Copenhagen.
We can no longer say: it's time, said the Beninese singer Angelique Kidjo.
In Africa, rivers and streams are drying up, and we can walk in them now, and we never could before.
For the first time in the history of climate diplomacy, which was born in 1992 with the adoption of the UN Convention, the movement to fight for a different world has approached environmental organizations.
French MEP José Bové, one of the figures in the fight for another world, said he had come to Copenhagen to "link climate and social justice". "At present there is no difference between fighting against global warming and fighting for another world".
The first manifestations began in the Asia-Pacific region, which contains many islands particularly vulnerable to climate warming.
In Australia, organizers say about 50,000 people took to the streets.
In Manila, several hundred people, mostly students, marched in red clothing and scarves evoking the importance of solar energy.
In Hong Kong, Jakarta, and Canada, several hundred demonstrators took to the streets to demand strong action against climate change.
In France, hundreds of people participated in the protests organized by the "350" movement, mainly in Paris, Marseille (south), Lille (north), Bordeaux (west) and Lyon (east).
A few dozen people gathered in Geneva.
Separatist Abkhazia elects its president, Georgia condemns it as a "fracas"
Abkhazia elected its president on Saturday, about a year after Moscow recognized the pro-Russian separatist territory as independent from Georgia, with Tbilisi calling the move a "fracas".
Some 131,000 people were allowed to participate in these first elections since the August 2008 Russo-Georgian war for control of South Ossetia, another former Georgian territory recognized by Russia.
The polling stations closed at 17h00 GMT.
According to the Abkhaz Election Commission officials, the voter turnout was 58% a few hours before the polls closed.
The first preliminary results should be announced on the night of Saturday to Sunday.
Five candidates, including incumbent President Sergei Bagapsh, categorically reject the idea of merging with Georgia, which has condemned these elections.
This election is a farce.
On the other hand, Georgian President Mikheil Saakashvili "regrets that Abkhazia has completely fallen into Russian control", said his spokeswoman, Manana Manjgaladze.
Other than Russia, only Nicaragua and Venezuela have recognized the independence of this territory of 216,000 people, while the rest of the world considers it part of Georgia, which was illegally occupied by Russian troops.
After separating from Georgia, after the 1992-93 conflict, in which several thousand people died, Abkhazia is trying to show through elections that it is ready to return to international politics.
This process is one of the stages of our new life, the new era of our independent state, Kvarčija Svetlana, a 54-year-old historian who also admitted to having voted for President Bagapsh, told AFP.
