The geography and history subjects will be strengthened as part of the reform of the general secondary school, Chatel said.
Education Minister Luc Chatel said in an interview with JDD on Sunday that the subjects of history and geography will be "enhanced" as part of the reform of the general high schools, even though their teaching will no longer be compulsory in the last year of high school with a focus on exact sciences.
Now all second-year students will have four hours a week and the same general culture program for all, Chatel confirmed.
According to the Minister, "hypocrisy must end", because according to him, the S specialization is no longer focused on exact sciences" but "in fact, the best students are in it".
The ES and L specialisations cannot be sub-specialisations for the S, he continues, and stresses: 'I have not heard many historians and intellectuals complaining that geography and history are not taught in the last year of vocational schools'.
An Ifop poll published by Humanité on Saturday showed that seven in ten French people (69%) disagree with the government's plan to abolish compulsory history and geography in the S-specialization high school graduation year, which is why many intellectuals and teachers have criticized the abolishment, both from the left and some members of the right.
The Minister added that it was "not possible" to abolish philosophy in the Master's programme.
