The UDF is raising the tone and calling on the Nouveau Centre party not to continue to use their abbreviation.
The UDF, controlled by the MoDem party of François Bayrou, reacted on Friday to the attempt by Nouveau Centre party president Hervé Morin to appropriate the acronym of Giscard's former party, saying that the acronym could not be used in any media under threat of prosecution.
Hervé Morin has publicly announced his intention to adopt the acronym UDF, saying that François Bayrou does not deserve to carry its legacy after extending his hand to the left.
The Minister of Defense, whose party is a partner of the UMP, was planning to confirm this strategy on Saturday before the National Council of the Nouveau Centre (NC).
This move was supported by Hervé de Charette (former pro-UMP now for NC), who claims ownership of the UDF trademark, as he was the first to register it with the National Institute of Industrial Property (l'Institut national de la propriété industrielle) in 2004.
But on Friday night, the committee of the UDF Association, led by friend Françoise Bayrou, who has no intention of being expropriated, broke their silence and formally requested the minister and the MPs to stop using the acronym and hand back the trademark, under threat of criminal prosecution.
In recent days, you have made alarming statements about your proposal to your political movement to re-adopt the UDF acronym, the Association writes in a letter signed by 19 of the 24 members of the committee, including François Bayrou and Marielle de Sarnez of the MoDem party and Senator Jean Arthuis of the Alliance Centriste.
At the same time, you have considered it appropriate to place the name +Nouveau centre+ on your promotional material and on the welcoming website of your movement, with the slogan +UDF today+", note the signatories of the letter.
As you know, you have no right to use this abbreviation, explains the UDF committee, which requests the NC "to immediately remove all mentions of the UDF name from all promotional materials, including (its) websites".
It also asks Hervé de Charette 'to transfer the ownership of the trade mark to the legitimate owners'.
If you do not, we will go to court to ensure that the law and the legitimate rights of UDF members are respected, the signatories warn.
In their letter, they state that the UDF "has been a full-fledged political movement since 1978" and recall that Mr. Morin and his friends "choose" to leave in 2007 "to create a competitive movement, as others did in 2002 to establish the UMP.
The Nouveau Centre therefore had no right to use the acronym UDF (Union for French Democracy).
They also recall that the last UDF congress voted in 2007 to join the MoDem for three years and to create a committee to defend the "moral and material interests" of the association founded by Valéry Giscard d'Estaing.
As regards Hervé de Charette, the Committee continues, 'when he registered the trade mark, he had been a member of the UMP for three years, not of the UDF'.
He has used the non-existent registration of acronyms in a scandalous and fraudulent manner to do so on his own account.
This tactlessness is beginning to be transformed into a crime, they declare, and then they speak ironically about the strategy of the NC: "It seems to us that in politics as in everyday life it is more valuable to make a name for oneself than to emerge from anonymity by fraudulently adopting a name to which we have no right".
