In his speech in Oslo, Obama won praise from the right wing for his "just war".
The American right on Friday welcomed the speech Barack Obama delivered the previous day in Oslo, content with the fact that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize winner advocated the concept of "just war" against the enemies of the United States.
Conservatives who had initially mocked Obama's award on October 9th applauded the presidential speech, including Sarah Palin, the former vice presidential candidate in the 2008 election.
I liked what he said, Palin, the Republican right-wing muse, told USA Today, adding that she herself has spoken about the subject of "sometimes necessary" war in her memoir, which is being published.
Of course, war is the last thing Americans want to be busy with, but it's necessary.
All terrorists must be held there, he thinks.
President Obama, who inherited two wars in Afghanistan and Iraq from his predecessor George W. Bush, justified the deployment of forces in Oslo on Thursday, using the speech to explain his decision to send another 30,000 troops to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another Obama opponent, Newt Gingrich, said the president had done a "very good job" in Oslo.
I think it was a really good speech, congratulating the former Speaker of the House of Representatives, who particularly appreciated the president's mention of "the existence of evil in the world".
In some ways, I thought it was quite historic, said Gingrich during an interview on the radio show "The Takeaway".
The former congressman, who some consider a possible Republican candidate for the 2012 presidential election, was thrilled to see a "left-wing president" remind the Nobel Prize committee members "that they themselves would not be free and could not pass on the peace prize if there was no use of force".
According to Michael Gerson, former speechwriter for George W. Bush, now editor of the Washington Post, Obama delivered a "very American speech".
Not only did he introduce himself as a "citizen of the world" as he always did, but he "spoke like an American president" and reminded Europeans "that they live in a safe bubble that they did not create and that they do not do much to preserve it", Gerson said.
Among the few right-wing dissenters is Bush-era hawk former UN ambassador John Bolton, who called the speech "uniform, pompous and uninspired", as reported on the website National Review Online.
To the left of the president, for example, Democratic Rep. Dennis Kucinich is horrified to see Barack Obama justify the use of force.
"When we wrap war in the garb of justice, we can easily justify the slaughter of innocent people", he warned.
However, the center-left press has taken a favorable view of the president.
Although the Los Angeles Times still considers Obama's peace prize award premature, it called his performance "over-the-top", even for a speaker known for his talent.
The Oslo speech should serve as a guide for international decisions in resolving conflicts, fighting poverty and oppression", the California Daily enthusiastically reports.
Obama "gave the speech he needed", the New York Times said, calling it "simple and informative".
Road haulage: three marathons to a deal that saves a supply shipment for Christmas.
After three marathon negotiations, the road transport unions and the TLF, the only employer organization that stayed on, reached an agreement Friday night that ended the call for a strike and the threat that hung over the delivery of Christmas supplies.
Transport Secretary Dominique Bussereau expressed "joy" at the signing of the agreement on Friday, after several negotiations that began Wednesday morning.
After a second night of discussions, negotiators broke off early Friday morning in the hope that the text of the agreement would be signed as soon as the morning was over.
This is despite the fact that three employers' organisations (FNTR, Unostra, OTRE) withdrew from the negotiations.
But it took more than six hours of meetings, starting at 11 a.m., to get everyone to agree and sign the agreement at 6 p.m.
This "would greatly damage businesses" and "risk disrupting the end-of-year celebrations", Bussereau said.
The text contains a 4% increase in wages for the lowest wages (local and regional road transport) and a 2.9% increase for the highest wages (international transport).
The hourly rate for the lowest wage increases from €8.72 to €9.06.
It is not much, but there is a lot of effort behind it, explained Patrice Clos (FO).
Tonight we're going to give our members an order to no blockades, no blockades of supply centers.
But there may be a few more opponents who are not satisfied", he added.
Philippe Grillot, president of the TLF, welcomed the "right deal", although it was difficult to concede a high wage increase due to international competition.
According to him, the lowest wage will increase by €170 per month and the highest wage by €100 to €120.
This was an agreement of common sense and respect for employees, said CMaxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) welcomed the "historic agreement".
This is an acceptable compromise, according to Richard Jaubert (CGT).
The agreement also provides for a 3% increase in travel costs and a report on the road transport situation in the first half of 2010, which will also allow the 13th salary issue and the modernisation of the collective agreement to be addressed.
Bussereau recalled the 'reduction of €100 million in corporate payroll taxes' which was the subject of the government's amendment to the draft budget bill for 2009, voted on by the National Assembly on Thursday night.
The government will ask the Senate for a "consensus" vote.
The signature allows the agreement to be applied first to the enterprises that are members of the organisation, and later to the whole sector, in the case of an extension by the Ministry of Labour.
It will be implemented "within the shortest possible time", Bussereau assured.
The whole process can only be slowed down by the disapproval of the employers' organisations.
The FNTR calls it a 'bad trade', as €100 million 'has already been offered to the sector as part of the carbon tax compensation'.
The Secretary of State for Transport has forced us to take emergency action not as a result of a mutual analysis, but to avoid angering turkey eaters at the approaching Christmas holidays, Unostra complained.
Otre said the agreement could "burial a large number of small and medium-sized enterprises in the sector" in the next 12 months.
