The Turkish justice has been melted for the Kurdish party and this decision has grave consequences.
Turkey's Constitutional Court ruled on Friday to dissolve the country's main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that prompted protests and demonstrations in the Kurdish community in the country's southeast and in Istanbul.
This decision may complicate the government's efforts to extend a hand of friendship to the Kurdish community in an attempt to end 25 years of conflict.
The Party for Democratic Society (DTP) was dissolved because it became "a breeding ground for activities that threaten the independence of the state and its indivisible unity", Supreme Court President Hashim Kilic told reporters after four days of deliberations.
The decision was adopted unanimously by 11 judges, with a majority of seven votes needed to dissolve the party, Kiliç said, adding that 37 party cadres, including its president Ahmet Türk and MP Aysely Tugluk, are banned from political life for five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr Türk and Ms Tugluk and the confiscation of the party's assets by the Ministry of Finance.
The DTP party has 21 seats in the parliament (out of 500).
The party leadership had already warned before the verdict that MPs would rather leave Parliament than serve as non-affiliated MPs.
The decision is a continuation of the trial launched in 2007 by the Prosecutor of the Court of Cassation, Abdurrahman Yalcinkay, who accuses the DTP of obeying the "orders" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), which Ankara and many countries consider a terrorist organization.
Many observers are convinced that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
The party claims to have no "basic connection" with the PKK, but refuses to label it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The court's verdict comes as the government extends a hand of friendship to the Kurdish community, offering a series of measures to strengthen their rights and trying to curb Kurdish support for the PKK and end the conflict.
DTP leadership confirmed that the dissolution of the party could lead to renewed tensions in Southeastern Anatolia, where in recent weeks many demonstrations against the conditions of the detention of PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan have been turned into clashes with the police.
Since the announcement of the court ruling, thousands of protesters have gathered outside the DTP headquarters in Diyarbakir, a major city in the southeast populated mostly by Kurds.
Police used tear-gas and water cannons, while protesters threw Molotov cocktails or fired stones from their stretchers.
About a hundred people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Mr. Türk said that the verdict of justice only "deepened the despair".
Turkey cannot solve this issue by banning the party, he said in the press.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also condemned the decision.
We're against interference by parties.
It solves nothing, said Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
This decision is a complete departure from the democratic proposals that the government has initiated, commented political scientist Ahmet Insel.
Of course, we can expect a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed responsibility for one of the deadliest attacks in the north of Turkey, which killed seven soldiers three days earlier.
