The cradle of the dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: a six-foot-two-inch-long animal with two strong hind limbs, an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short forelimbs with serrated claws, and a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have been nothing special.
Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues write in Thursday's issue of Science that the Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs to have these body markings.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then in the equatorial dry zone of the supercontinent Pangea.
Tawa opens a new window on the earlier evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It tells us a lot about the kin, the distribution and the markings of early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavating at the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes we find a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unheard of for Triassic sediments, says team member Randall Irmis of the Museum of Natural History in Utah.
Some of the bones were quickly identified by scientists as a new species.
During the excavations, they collected the remains of five individuals.
The find confirms the theory of the early history of dinosaurs.
The name "Tawa" comes from the Hopi sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an unusual find: "Fossils of Triassic dinosaurs are very rare, mostly found in single fragments".
Other dinosaur experts do not share this enthusiasm without reservation.
The find is not particularly spectacular, but it does confirm some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current scientific opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the placement of pradinosaurs is often disputed.
For example, experts discuss when lizards split into three major lines of evolution: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the Tyrannosaurus rex, Velociraptor, and birds; the "long-necked" four-legged sauropods and their relatives; and the herbivorous Ornithischia, which included such species as Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
Tawa hallae is the original therapod, according to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues.
It exhibits an interesting combination of primitive and advanced qualities, says Nesbitt.
For example, researchers have found evidence of air sacs on the skulls of Tawa hallae, which are also found in the descendants of theropod birds.
The air sacs make the birds' breathing more efficient than that of mammals.
At the Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were apparently partially filled with air.
The Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air pockets, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of giant sauropods later also had air sacs and light bones, this useful innovation was probably created by a common ancestor of both groups.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, scientists have concluded that lizards first appeared there.
According to this, the three lines of evolution split early and spread from South America to all the continents that then formed the single landmass as the supercontinent of Pangea.
It would also be a good sign if the team found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods along with the Tawa hallae.
The three cannot have descended from a common immigrant ancestor, argue the scientists.
We believe that there were at least three waves of migration into North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the scientific study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, one of the heaviest dinosaurs, lived in what is now Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His suggestion might paint a distorted picture, because South America has preserved many primitive dinosaur fossils, while other continents rarely have any.
How dinosaurs evolved from a relatively rare secondary lineage of reptiles to the ruling vertebrates on Earth during the Earth's Middle Ages is still a mystery.
During the Triassic, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, including the ancestors of today's crocodiles and flying lizards and countless other lizards.
Around the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread across the world and many new species evolved, while relatives died out and the Triassic and Jurassic intersected.
The success story didn't last forever.
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass extinction, which the dinosaurs happened to survive, but the reptiles didn't.
Or dinosaurs adapted better, so they could outsmart their competition.
The success story didn't last forever, anyway.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact helped another group of animals that also evolved in the Triassic and has lived in the shadows ever since: mammals.
