75% of working mothers have work-related problems related to motherhood.
Discrimination in employment has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who are about to have a child.
This is the result of the study 'Fertility and the working career of Spanish women' carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The study involved 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, and the results are clear: 75% of working mothers have limited opportunities in the labour market because of motherhood.
The study highlights that there are many differences in views on the number of children at the beginning of a partnership, depending on whether they work or not, and also on the type of employment.
Women who do not work outside the home, work part-time or have no stable job, live with their partner earlier, have their first child earlier and have more children overall.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, especially in the public sector, delay both cohabitation and motherhood, and have fewer children.
"Women aged 35-49 with stable jobs have their first child on average 3.7 years after the start of their life with their partner.This figure is 4.1 for women who have devoted a greater part of their lives to achieving stable employment and have therefore had to postpone both their life together and the arrival of their children.
The type of occupation also has a strong influence on motherhood, although it has a smaller influence on the time of initiation of cohabitation with a partner", explains Margarita Delgado, a researcher at CSIC.
Another factor affecting the age of women at the time of marriage and childbirth is the degree of education.
Research shows that the higher the education level, the higher the age at which women get married and have their first child.
Differences also exist between women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, women with basic and higher education had their first child at 25.1 and 32.1 respectively.
"There is another difference between women depending on their level of education.
Women with a primary education marry and have their first child before finding stable employment, while women with secondary or higher education, on the contrary, prefer to obtain stable employment before marrying and having their first child", says Delgado.
