Light commercial vehicles are increasing in sales
After almost two years, the light commercial vehicle market is starting to recover.
The 9,425 vehicles registered in Spain in November represented an increase of 12.6% compared with 2008, and what is more, it is the first increase after 22 months of sustained decline, according to figures from the patronage organisation of manufacturers Anfac and dealers Ganvam.
However, a positive figure is better to put in quarantine, as November 2008 is a very bad period for comparison and marked a 60% decrease compared to the previous year.
As a result, despite the increase in the last month, the total number of registered vehicles in the last 11 months is 40% less than in the previous financial year.
Since January, 95.853 vehicles have been sold, which includes all possible vehicles falling into the category of light commercial vehicles: passenger car derivatives, pick-ups, vans, small trucks and light trucks/crossovers.
And the clouds that are the biggest drain on demand have not disappeared either, even though they were bought by private individuals, most of the purchases were made by small and medium-sized firms and almost 100% of the purchases are financed through third parties.
In addition to the constraints resulting from the closure of the bank credit source, there are other factors such as the cessation of activity or the continuation of a bad economic situation.
In this situation, unlike passenger cars, the aid for the purchase of 2000E did not help much.
In addition to private individuals, there are also those who are small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) who intend to buy a light commercial vehicle up to 3,5 tonnes with a CO2 emission level of not more than 160 grams per kilometre, but the number of transactions has been confirmed.
Just yesterday, Ganvam again reminded us that special attention needs to be paid to the management of these vehicles as well as industrial vehicles (trucks and buses).
The dealers association expects the trend in 2010 to be similar to last year, with sales of passenger cars and 4x4s estimated to fall by 19%.
The brake assist system is already mandatory.
As with the ABS, ESP stability control, and manual brake systems will all become mandatory on European cars.
In fact, they are already part of the mandatory equipment of all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the others, the deadline for removing the deficiency is set, which is February 2011.
The EU measure aims to improve pedestrian protection and works in such a way that it can help prevent many collisions.
The auxiliary hand brake system shall increase the pressure on the brake in an emergency, which the system shall detect after the driver has stepped.
But it doesn't always manage to keep that pressure up to the end.
According to a study by the automobile parts manufacturer Bosch, a third of the drivers who have an accident fail to apply the brakes before a collision, and half of them fail to use the brakes to their full potential.
1,100 accidents in all
On the contrary, this aid requires the braking system to its fullest extent, and shortens the braking distance of the vehicle.
According to a study carried out in the EU alone, if all vehicles were equipped with this type of device, up to 1 100 pedestrian fatalities could be avoided annually.
The reduction will be even more significant - by calculations one in four personal injury accidents would be avoided - following the introduction of so-called intelligent hand brake systems.
In this case, the vehicle will be equipped with a system which (using radar or camera) detects and reports obstacles to the driver, except for light braking.
If the driver responds, it will help him to increase the pressure on the pedal if necessary.
If the driver fails to react, even if a collision cannot be avoided, the device shall apply the brake with the greatest possible intensity and minimise the risk of damage.
